pold von Sacher-Masoch and Alfred Döblin; Weimar intellectuals such as Erich Wulffen and psychoanalyst Viola Bernard. The results are important new insights into the continuing legacy of such writers and into the agency increasingly claimed by the readerships that emerged with the development of modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aEuropean literature.  acase study.  acriminality.  ahistory of sexuality.  amodernity.  apsychoanalysis.  areaders.  asexual publics.1 aDamousi, Joy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDamousi, Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLang, Birgit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Alison, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLewis, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526106117zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526106117zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526106117/original  a978-3-11-128281-7 Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA